  "primerTitle": "IPA core symbols — quick recap",
  "primer": "The **International Phonetic Alphabet** gives one symbol per speech sound. **Consonants** are named by three things: *voicing* (voiceless / voiced), *place* of articulation (where in the mouth, e.g. bilabial, alveolar, velar), and *manner* (how, e.g. plosive, nasal, fricative, affricate, approximant). **Vowels** are named by *height* (close … open), *backness* (front … back), and *rounding* (rounded / unrounded). This deck covers the core symbols below.\n\n**Consonants — symbol → name (example):**\n- **p** — voiceless bilabial plosive ('pat')\n- **b** — voiced bilabial plosive ('bat')\n- **t** — voiceless alveolar plosive ('tap')\n- **d** — voiced alveolar plosive ('dab')\n- **k** — voiceless velar plosive ('cat')\n- **g** — voiced velar plosive ('gap')\n- **ʔ** — glottal stop ('uh-oh')\n- **m** — bilabial nasal ('map')\n- **n** — alveolar nasal ('nap')\n- **ŋ** — velar nasal ('sing')\n- **f** — voiceless labiodental fricative ('fan')\n- **v** — voiced labiodental fricative ('van')\n- **θ** — voiceless dental fricative ('thin')\n- **ð** — voiced dental fricative ('this')\n- **s** — voiceless alveolar fricative ('sip')\n- **z** — voiced alveolar fricative ('zip')\n- **ʃ** — voiceless postalveolar fricative ('ship')\n- **ʒ** — voiced postalveolar fricative ('measure')\n- **h** — voiceless glottal fricative ('hat')\n- **tʃ** — voiceless postalveolar affricate ('church')\n- **dʒ** — voiced postalveolar affricate ('judge')\n- **ɹ** — alveolar approximant ('red')\n- **j** — palatal approximant ('yes')\n- **w** — voiced labial-velar approximant ('wet')\n- **l** — alveolar lateral approximant ('left')\n\n**Vowels — symbol → name (example):**\n- **i** — close front unrounded ('see')\n- **ɪ** — near-close near-front unrounded ('sit')\n- **e** — close-mid front unrounded (French 'é')\n- **ɛ** — open-mid front unrounded ('bed')\n- **æ** — near-open front unrounded ('cat')\n- **a** — open front unrounded (Spanish 'a')\n- **ə** — mid-central (schwa, 'about')\n- **ʌ** — open-mid back unrounded ('cup')\n- **ɑ** — open back unrounded ('father')\n- **ɔ** — open-mid back rounded ('thought')\n- **o** — close-mid back rounded (French 'eau')\n- **ʊ** — near-close near-back rounded ('put')\n- **u** — close back rounded ('boot')\n- **y** — close front rounded (French 'u')\n\n**Special cases:** **tʃ** and **dʒ** are *affricates* (a plosive that releases into a fricative); **ɹ** is the English 'r' (distinct from a trill); **ə** (schwa) is the neutral unstressed vowel; **j** is the consonant 'y' sound, not a vowel.",
